	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Risk management in an era of price volatility</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC has posted its latest update on agricultural commodity and food price developments in the EU. This review is based on data available in November 2010. It reveals that average EU prices for agricultural commodities between November 2009 and November 2010 increased: 66% for soft wheat and barley; 53% for maize; 22% for durum wheat; 23% for butter; 21% for Edam cheese; 5% for skimmed-milk powder (SMP); 14% for poultry; 6% for beef and 3% for pork. While prices had been increasing for many months, by November 2010 ‘they were still below the peak reached in 2007/08’. Indeed, from October to November 2010, prices for SMP and butter declined, while prices for maize and pork were unchanged.</p><p>In terms of EU consumer prices, prices over all food categories in November 2010 were 2.6% above prices in November 2009. However, prices were 6.6% higher in November 2007 compared to November 2010. In this context it should be borne in mind that in terms of food price formation at the retail level, ‘non-agricultural cost components … have a much greater weight on food price inflation than changes in the prices of raw agricultural components.’</p><p>European farmers, meanwhile, are increasingly having to get to grips with the use of risk management strategies as a means of maximising farm incomes in an era of rising cost and heightened price volatility. At a recent seminar in Ireland, a UK farm manager explained the strategies he had adopted to manage the risks associated with price fluctuations. According to one press report, ‘he sells one quarter of the anticipated harvest before the crop is planted, one quarter around the time of planting when the crop areas are confirmed. One quarter is sold through the growing season right up to harvest and the final quarter is sold post harvest, once the harvest is safely in store and the exact quantities are known’. He told seminar participants, ‘I may not hit the market highs with all my grain, but I don’t end up at the market lows. My average is what matters and over the last seven years I have been in the top half of the market average and have been able to reinvest in my business.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
EC, ‘January 2011 update on recent agricultural commodity and food price developments in the EU’, file note, D (2011) 98085 - 100525, 31 January 2011<br />

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/food01_2011_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/food01_2011_...</a><br />
EC, Agriculture and rural development directorate website, archive of previous updates on the evolution of commodity and food price developments in the EU<br />

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/archive_en.htm" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/markets/foodprices/archive_en.htm</a><br />
<i>TheDairySite.com</i>, ‘Managing grain price volatility’, 31 January 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.thedairysite.com/news/33407/managing-grain-price-volatility" target="_self">http://www.thedairysite.com/news/33407/managing-grain-price-volatility</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC’s latest figures reveal the strong price recovery in EU agricultural commodity prices during 2010. However it is unclear to what extent these price increases are translating into improved farm-gate prices. This is likely to be critically dependent on the risk management strategies adopted by individual EU farmers, and is a new reality for most EU farmers that has only emerged with the dismantling of price-guarantee arrangements. Increasingly reference prices, where they remain, are set at safety-net levels, significantly below normal market prices.</p><p>From an ACP perspective, the question arises of how ACP producers can be assisted in establishing and effectively using risk management strategies at the farm level, so that they are better able to deal with increased price volatility. What is clear is that if well-organised EU farmers are facing challenges in this area, then the challenges are significantly greater for the vast majority of ACP farmers. This raises important questions about the role of public policy in regulating relationships along supply chains in an era of heightened price instability. Public policies on strengthening the functioning of specific supply chains could potentially play an important role in assisting farmers to develop risk management strategies to ensure that they fully benefit from price rises, and are not disproportionately disadvantaged by price declines. In this way, greater resilience could be built up in coping with periodic price declines, thereby avoiding any undermining of the agricultural production base in ACP countries (particularly among smallholder farmers).</p>
		</div>
		
